{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e6556acc-883f-43c6-97f2-6f01646f363b","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates one instance **per HTTP request** — each request is a natural scope boundary. In MAUI, **there is no per-request scope**. The app has a single long-lived scope (the app's lifetime), so `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`. Your DbContext is created once and reused forever, causing stale/cached data.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient`** — gives each injection a fresh DbContext:\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddTransient<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n2. **Use `IDbContextFactory`** (preferred for more control):\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n   Then inject and create short-lived contexts explicitly:\n   ```csharp\n   public MyViewModel(IDbContextFactory<MyDbContext> factory)\n   {\n       using var db = factory.CreateDbContext();\n       // ...\n   }\n   ```\n\nThe factory approach is generally recommended because it makes the context lifetime explicit and avoids accidentally holding a long-lived context reference in a transient service.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2faf5f0a-9d7b-425e-8565-136c0c74ca05","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common pitfall when moving from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request (each request is a \"scope\"). In MAUI, there's no concept of an HTTP request — the app has a single long-lived scope (essentially the app's lifetime), so `AddScoped` behaves like `AddSingleton`. That's why the DbContext persists across page navigations.","outputTokens":432,"requestId":"9BC0:21A8FE:61F2841:6D336A0:69EC10D5"},"id":"49a9261d-c4fa-47d9-a427-f5f837dc57d8","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:54:54.831Z","parentId":"5be9ce5a-8c2c-49e4-882b-a62e7a353124"}
